{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Chart Understanding is divided into three tasks: Chart Summarization: (1) Unicharts: a model that processes visual elements through a chart encoder and text decoder to generate natural language summaries [135]; Chart Question Answering: (2) STL-CQA: a structured Transformer model to localize chart elements and perform cross-modal reasoning [136],(3) OpenCQA: Multiple foundation models were fine-tuned to answer open-ended questions with charts [42]; Chart Retrieval: (4) WYTIWYR: a user intent-aware framework with multimodal inputs for visualization retrieval [137].",
    "led to their increase in automatic content recognition and extraction.",
    "A notable example was MATCHA [140], which was designed based on the encoder-decoder structure of the Pix2Struct model and achieved chart-to-table conversion through end-to-end training.",
    "The model employed a Transformer architecture with 300 million parameters and was fine-tuned on real-world chart-table pairs to generate linearized tables.",
    "On the basis, Deplot [36] further fine-tuned MATCHA by focusing exclusively on the task of chartto-table conversion."
  ],
